
================================================================================
  MONTE CARLO SIMULATION REPORT
  Michele Piazzoli — Data Analysis
================================================================================


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  WHAT IS THIS REPORT?
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  This report answers one question: "What if I had taken the same trades,
  but in a completely different order?"

  We took all 948 historical trades and shuffled them into
  10,000 random sequences. Every simulation uses the exact same
  trades — same wins, same losses, same amounts. Only the order changes.

  Because the trades are identical, every simulation ends at the same
  final balance: $+700,330.54. What changes is the path
  to reach that balance.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ORIGINAL STRATEGY SNAPSHOT
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Starting Capital:         $+100,000.00
  Final Balance:            $+700,330.54
  Net Profit:               $+600,330.54
  Total Return:             +600.33%

  Total Trades:             948
  Wins:                     332 (35.0%)
  Losses:                   616 (65.0%)
  Average Win:              $+6,820.95
  Average Loss:             $-2,701.67

  The win rate is 35.0%, but winning trades are significantly
  larger than losing trades (avg win $+6,820.95 vs avg loss
  $-2,701.67). This is what drives profitability.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DRAWDOWNS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  A drawdown is when the account drops from its highest point. It measures
  the worst temporary loss experienced before recovering. Across all
  10,000 simulations, here is the range of worst-case drawdowns:

  Best case (luckiest order):         -9.69%   ($-34,133.82)
  Typical case (median):             -26.89%   ($-65,534.57)
  Bad case:                          -54.30%   ($-100,798.65)
  Worst case (unluckiest order):    -133.30%   ($-163,413.98)

  How to read this: in a typical scenario, the account will at some
  point be about 27% below its peak before recovering.
  In a bad scenario, this could reach 54% or more.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  RISK OF RUIN
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  What is the chance the account drops to a given level at any point?

  Loss Level          Threshold         Probability  Visual
