  In plain terms: there is a 52% chance the account will at some
  point be down 10%, a 16% chance of being down 30%, and a
  4% chance of being down 50%. All of these are temporary —
  every simulation ends in profit.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  UNDERWATER PERIODS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  An underwater period is a streak of consecutive trades where the account
  stays below its previous high.

  For how many trades the strategy stayed without seeing a new peak?

  Shortest drought:           36 trades
  Typical drought (median):   128 trades
  Long drought:               247 trades
  Longest drought ever:       480 trades


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  PROBABILITY OF PROFIT OVER TIME
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  How likely is the account to be in profit at different stages?

  Stage                          Trades  Prob. of Profit       Avg Balance
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  25% (237/948)                     237            99.0%      $+250,487.10
  50% (474/948)                     474           100.0%      $+401,052.19
  75% (711/948)                     711           100.0%      $+550,253.13
  100% (948/948)                    948           100.0%      $+700,330.54

  Even just a quarter of the way through, 99% of simulations
  are already in profit. By the halfway point, the strategy is
  profitable in virtually every scenario.


